llenges old understandings of the Gaelic community as a single collective identity, making it an invaluable resource for students, lecturers and researchers interested in questions of linguistic diversity, linguistic minorities and language policy and planning.The first in-depth investigation of Gaelic based on sociolinguistic analysis Draws on the latest scholarship and expertise developed by the Soillse research network for Gaelic revitalisation Offers fresh perspectives from notable early career scholars together with internationally recognised experts in small language revitalization  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 4aLanguage & Linguistics. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / General.2bisacsh1 aArmstrong, Timothy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBell, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBirnie, Ingeborg, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarty, Nicola, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChristmas, Cassie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDunbar, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDunmore, Stuart, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacLeod, Kirstie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacLeod, Marsaili, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacleod, Michelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcConville, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcLeod, Wilson, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMunro, Gillian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNicLeòid, Sìleas, econtributor.4ct